  "doc_id": "31596",
  "text": "The influence of psychosocial stress on testosterone levels and semen quality has been also demonstrated in men. Guay et al. [CITATION_1] found a strong association between work stress and low testosterone level. Furthermore, psychosocial stress was associated with decreased semen quality in fertile men. [CITATION_2] Male occupational stress is also associated with sperm damage [CITATION_3] and decreased number of conceptions. [CITATION_4] Healthy men were examined to evaluate several socio-psycho-behavioral factors in China, and psychological stress is associated with semen quality. [CITATION_5] Despite several reports of the influence of stress stimuli on the testes, one important point has not been addressed, which is whether ORIGINAL ARTICLE Immediate and late effects of chronic stress in the testes of prepubertal and adult rats Experimental design Four groups of age-matched (prepubertal and adult) rats categorized by age were used to evaluate the immediate effects of stress stimuli at the beginning of the experiment. The SP-I group (n = 10) was composed of 4-week-old rats (stressed prepubertal animals killed immediately after 10 weeks of life) and the SA-I group (n = 9) was composed of 10-week-old rats (stressed adult animals killed immediately after 16 weeks of life); both groups were subjected to the same stress stimuli. We compared each of these groups with age-matched control groups: CP-I group (n = 10, control prepubertal animals killed immediately after 10 weeks of life) and CA-I group (n = 9, control adult animals killed immediately after 16 weeks of life) ( Table 1) .",
